<doc id="40792" wikidata="Q4915487" url="?curid=40792" title="Bipolar signal">
<text>In telecommunications, a bipolar signal is a signal which may assume either of two polarities, neither of which is zero. 

A bipolar signal may have a two-state non-return-to-zero (NRZ) or a three-state return-to-zero (RZ) binary coding scheme. 

A bipolar signal is usually symmetrical with respect to zero amplitude, &quot;i.e.&quot; the absolute values of the positive and negative signal states are nominally equal. Contrast with unipolar encoding where one state is zero amplitude.

