=== As a limiting case of infinite ladder networks ===

==== Intuition ====


Consider an infinite ladder network consisting of a series impedance formula_68 and a shunt admittance formula_69 Let its input impedance be formula_70 If a new pair of impedance formula_68 and admittance formula_72 is added in front of the network, its input impedance formula_73 remains unchanged since the network is infinite. Thus, it can be reduced to a finite network with one series impedance formula_68 and two parallel impedances formula_75 and formula_76 Its input impedance is given by the expression

:formula_77

which is also known as its iterative impedance. Its solution is:

:formula_78

For a transmission line, it can be seen as a limiting case of an infinite ladder network with infinitesimal impedance and admittance at a constant ratio. Taking the positive root, this equation simplifies to:

:formula_79

==== Derivation ====

Using this insight, many similar derivations exist in several books and are applicable to both lossless and lossy lines.

Here, we follow an approach posted by Tim Healy. The line is modeled by a series of differential segments with differential series elements formula_80 and shunt elements formula_81 (as shown in the figure at the beginning of the article). The characteristic impedance is defined as the ratio of the input voltage to the input current of a semi-infinite length of line. We call this impedance formula_62 That is, the impedance looking into the line on the left is formula_62 But, of course, if we go down the line one differential length formula_84 the impedance into the line is still formula_62 Hence we can say that the impedance looking into the line on the far left is equal to formula_86 in parallel with formula_87 and formula_88 all of which is in series with formula_89 and formula_90 Hence:
